                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I believe the first incarnation of the DKP system was set as a fixed point system, but today, there are probably as many variations of DKP as there are guilds.
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">The basics of a DKP system require </span>
<br />
A) a method of earning, 
<br />
B) a method of spending
<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">and usually (but optionally) </span>
<br />
C) a method of ensuring 'mathematical health' (e.i. vs. inflation or deflation), if A and B dont do this automatically.
<br />
D) a number rules and exceptions to adjust between 'common good for the guild' and 'individual fairness'. Like who can loot what, and how often, quest, refunds, flags, leaving the guild, changing mains, 2-boxers, alt looting, spells, 'warrior weapons', bows, last piece rules, looting for selling.
<br />
E) a way of displaying and updating points. Most often a simple list on a webboard, or by using the EQDKP system (www.eqdkp.com) which requires you to have a webspace and basic web knowledge to install.
<br />

<br />
If you are designing your system from the bottom, I suggest thinking very carefully and systematically about it, because there are lots of pitfalls, and even those who 'dont care about loot' will get angry if they percieve you to favorize others (and almost all rules can be twisted into a favortism argument if you try hard enough).
<br />

<br />
Try reading this thread for more info:
<br />
<a href="http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=6693" target="_blank">http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=6693</a>
<br />

<br />
If you are completely new to this, I suggest copying a system that someone else uses and go from there.[/url]</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
