                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Easiest system:
<br />

<br />
1 DKP per approved raid-hour.  (you could also tweak this on an encounter-by-encounter basis.  You could divide this by teir: Progression 2 DKP/hour, major 1.5 DKP/hour, minor 1.0 DKP/hour, trivial 0.5 DKP/hour.)
<br />

<br />
Items are bid on at the time of drop.  High bid gets the item.
<br />
You cannot bid more DKP than you have.
<br />

<br />
It has flaws, but it's the easiest to maintain, it deals with inflation/deflation, and it's quick to distribute loot.
<br />

<br />
Modifications:
<br />
Only 1 or 2 loots/day, or 2nd loot of a day costs a 50% extra tax. (discourages splurging)
<br />
Min bid is Y% of your current DKP. (discourages hoarding)
<br />
Max bid is Z% of your current DKP. (discourages splurging)
<br />
Bid system:
<br />
1&gt; Join a loot channel.  Say your bid price in channel.
<br />
2&gt; Send tells to someone.  That person announces current high bid (possibly in loot channel)
<br />
3&gt; Silent auction.  Send tells with a bid price.  Highest bid wins, pays what they bid.
<br />
4&gt; Silent auction.  Send tells with a bid price.  Highest bid wins, with a price between their bid and the 2nd highest bid.
<br />

<br />
Disadvantage: Your skill at bidding determines how much loot you get.
<br />

<br />
A slightly more complicated system that also doesn't require item pricing:
<br />
Items go for 3 prices:
<br />
Major Upgrade (20%)
<br />
Minor Upgrade (8%)
<br />
Rot (1%)
<br />

<br />
Major Upgrades cost you 20% of your current DKP.  Minor upgrades cost you 10% of your current DKP.  Rot costs you 1% of your current DKP.
<br />

<br />
Alts/recruits bid after main Minor upgrades.
<br />

<br />
Major upgrade purchases are ordered by current DKP.  Someone with 100 DKP outbids someone with 50 DKP.
<br />

<br />
Minor upgrade purchases are ordered by current DKP.  A major upgrade bid beats a minor upgrade bid, even of the minor is on someone with much more DKP.
<br />

<br />
Disadvantage: massively discourages DKP hoarding.  Heavy raiders before a progression phase feel like their DKP is burning a hole in their pocket.
<br />

<br />
Advantage: Same.  Heavy raiders will upgrade their gear as fast as they can, to prevent the % based system from making their gear too expensive.  They will also compete over who gets priority.  Nobody can get unreachably far ahead of everyone else: if you have 10 times more DKP than anyone else, you are 10 major upgrades away from parity.
<br />

<br />
Tweaks: The % cost of items determines how long it takes a new member to 'catch up'.  If one major upgrade happens per Y person-hours with a Z% cost per item, the median DKP will be (Y/(100%-Z%)).
<br />

<br />
A 'simple' DKP system needs to have no fixed item prices, because setting item prices is hard.
<br />

<br />
Rot pricing:
<br />
In a system with fixed prices, you probably want a rot safety valve.  Items that go for rot price are given at most a nominal price, and /randomed off to those who want it.  You may or may not have a 'needs' based price system, which I don't think they are wise.
<br />

<br />
Random DKP loot distribution systems:
<br />
1 DKP/raid hour.
<br />
People bid on the item by doing a /random 1 DKP_BID
<br />
Highest random wins, and pays that much DKP.
<br />
One roll per customer!
<br />

<br />
Non-DKP loot distribution systems:
<br />
Everyone who wants the item joins a channel.
<br />

<br />
Everyone who can use the item, but doesn't want it, /randoms.
<br />

<br />
Winner of the /random then picks who wins the item.
<br />

<br />
Disadvantage: Encourages cliques and popularity contest games.
<br />
Advantage: 0 maintenance.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
