                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">For those who have a lot of experience with DKP systems, particularly those in smaller, more casual guilds...is there a rough number of drops per time period below which the system doesn't function well?  If so, that might be important information for Fading Illusion to consider.
<br />

<br />
The last guild I was in used a loot council as well.  Worked well for us, although there were issues.  I was on the council, so got to see a lot of the inner workings.
<br />

<br />
It relies a lot on the perception of fairness.  You need to make sure that people believe that things are being handled fairly, no favoritism.  What the guild I was in did was keep a post on our boards with all loot awards for the last 3 months.  That gave people a reference to look at and refer to.  Members who might complain could look at the board and see just how long it had been since someone got something.  And the loot committee itself can refer to the list, which is good to avoid passing over people.  The quiet members of the guild can be easily overlooked.  More members makes it easier to insure you don't overlook people.  Less members results in faster decisions.  We also had several members of our loot council be elected, serving 3 months, staggered monthly.  The rest were officers.  
<br />

<br />
As with Nokei, when you last got loot was a big factor, assuming it was a nice item, of course.  Receiving an item that would otherwise have rotted doesn't have the same impact as having received an uber item.
<br />

<br />
Even with that, mistakes will be made.  And those serving on the loot council will probably receive a little less loot then they would have otherwise, err on the side of caution to avoid the perception of bias.  But in the long run, it is as fair as any other system...as long as the people involved in the decisions are trying to be fair.
<br />

<br />
I tried to encourage the guild to go DKP to remove the human element.  With a loot council, if people are unhappy with how loot is being dealt with, they are upset with a person.  With DKP, they are upset with the rules.  However, I do believe that adopting DKP can change a guild's nature.  The focus can shift to getting points to be able to get loot.  A shift to more raiding, less family.  Depends a lot on the leadership of course, but something to keep in mind.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Personally I think bidding systems are unfair. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Don't think it is unfair.  If you have points, you can spend it.  If the perceived value of an item changes, then it costs more or less.  No different than any other system.  Today's good item is tomorrow's junk.  Is it fair to pay 1500 for the best, and it being silk legs...and 2 months later, you've killed something new and now there's a new best...so it is now worth 1500?  You bet it is.  You know the risks of whatever system you use.  No system is perfect.  Know your system and run with it.  
<br />

<br />
The good thing about bidding though is the simplicity.  You just need to keep track of the points people get and spend.  The cost of items will sort itself out.  Very simple.  Great for a smaller, more casual guild.  
<br />

<br />
Ultimately, whatever system you wind up choosing, it is important that the people in the guild support the system and believe in it and how it is carried out.  That is the most important factor.  Any system can work, but it must have the support of those it applies to.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
