                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Like others, I do not recommend an award system at all. With the discussions surrounding it and assorted drama, you'll end up not saving any administrative workload at all. 
<br />

<br />
Dkp is the easiest system of them all. It's not perfect, but provided you do it well, does speed up loot awarding and significantly reduce drama.
<br />

<br />
An important thing to beware with dkp in a smaller guild is dkp inflation. It's very important that the dkp going in ends up being roughly equal to the dkp going out. What happens when you have inflation is that the amount of dkp that went out (loot) starts being dwarfed by the dkp awarded. The result, is that the people who raid the more are getting dkp faster than they can spend it, and if the inflation is really high, the dkp gap between those who are online every day vs those who are not will actually grow and keep growing, no matter how much people loot or don't. You'll end up with a looting list, and the same few people will receive loot over and over while the rest of the guild will rarely see anything. While this may not actually hurt the guild in progression, you'll miss out on one of the primary goal of dkp, which is distributing loot to everyone according to their attendance.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
	<tr>
