                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Our guild switched to DKP at about the time we started raiding Seru regularly.  The big difference in our system compared to the systems mentioned here is that we had no set point values for targets or loot.  We used a Vickery auction which takes much less time then the other methods posted here to determine loot value and winner.  The total number of points spent on loot were divided evenly with all players participating in the raid.  When we initially set this up, there were 1000 points per player and at the end there was still 1000 points per player.
<br />

<br />
The advantages over the fixed DKP systems listed here were:
<br />

<br />
1. No haggling or book keeping over value assignments for loot or targets.  More valuabled targets returned more points because the loot was worth more.
<br />

<br />
2. No inflation or deflation.  There were actually corrections that had to be made because incoming recruits earned points as recruits and members would leave taking their points out of circulation but they were very small and amounted to less then 2% of raid value.
<br />

<br />
3. Vickey auctions are very fast and arguably give a better results then the English auctions I have seen used.  Our guild could do a joint raid returning 4 items, bid on them all, and select the highest 2 before other guilds could even finish bidding on 1 item.
<br />

<br />
Problems we had which would be corrected if I set up another system:
<br />

<br />
1. Some classes (especially bards) had a bidding advantage for items because they had less competition for their upgrades.  There were ways to fix this but by the time we looked into it we had lost enough players to WoW and SOE's incompetence that it did not matter.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Banished Soul Talc
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">He either fears his fate too much,
<br />
or his desserts are small
<br />
who dares not put it to the touch,
<br />
to win or lose it all.</span> - Montrose</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
