                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Fading Illusion wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
For Loot Councils, how many were on the council. How did you vote?
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The LC was made up of non-officer members of the guild.  People volunteered, and the membership voted on who would serve (when the number of volunteers actually exceeded the slots available lol).
<br />

<br />
When we were around 60-80 mains, I think there were 10 members (as I noted we raided a few nights a week).  Our goal was to have 4-6 people serving on LC for each raid.  If your guild is smaller, say 40 mains - probably 6-8 people would be more than enough - especially if raid attendance is high.
<br />

<br />
Channel was created (yourguildnameloots) and passworded - no need for rank and file to be privy to the discussions (what's said in LC, stays in LC).  When something dropped, 1 person would take tells for the item.  If 4 items dropped, then one to each of 4 LC members.  The LC would then discuss each drop in turn - what was being replaced, if it could be passed down, etc.  I would say 80-90 pct of decisions were fairly cut and dry.  Others, the LC would discuss more.  In the end, the majority vote ruled.  I think we decided a minimum of 4 people had to be on a LC for a given raid.  In general, we maxed at around 7-8 people.  When not enough LC members were there, guild members were invited to serve temporarily.  One thing we avoided was putting people like puller, raid leader, MA/MT, MA/MT healer, heal channel coordinator, etc. on the LC.  Don't want to wipe because someone was distracted discussing loot.
<br />

<br />
Things became more complicated when we decided to go for Sleeper's Tomb as a guild.  The officers more or less kept track of which classes had keys and which were needed.  After the requisite classes were filled, max level (65 at the time) melee had priority (for weapons that proc avatar).  The caster drops in ST are complete junk anyhow.  
<br />

<br />
If you decide to key your guild for something - ST, VP, Emp/VT whatever - my suggestion is you discuss the plans for some time to get the best buy in from everyone as to how key / key parts will be awarded.  When people know in advance, they are less likely to be dissapointed with the results.
<br />

<br />
Happy to answer any other questions you might have.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
