                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Our set up was similiar to Nokei's, except the officers were on the loot committee, although if one were raid leader, he might not join in the loot decisions that raid.
<br />

<br />
Two bits of advice I can offer is this: 
<br />

<br />
1. Never promise loot to someone.  Not talking about doing an epic raid for Joe...that's for Joe obviously.  Just regular raids.  If a nice item drops and it is a tough choice between two people, don't promise the next drop to the other.  If you screw up and give it to person1 when it probably should have gone to person2, admit you screwed up and leave it at that.  The past can impact the current.  But the current should not decide the future.  In the future, the situation will be different than it is now.  So don't promise.  
<br />

<br />
2.  Don't shortcut the system.  We had our GL award an item once, before the council got to discuss.  However, the council would have awarded it to someone else.  Now you're in a bad decision...take an awarded item away and give it to whom it should have gone or stick with what happened.  I recommend letting the bad decision stand, personally, not nice to award a good person something and then take it away.  But regardless, it is a no win situation.  No matter how obvious it is, follow the procedure.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
	<tr>
		<td class="row2" width="150" align="left" valign="middle"><span class="nav"><a href="#top" class="nav">Back to top</a></span></td>
